"Pastene L.A., Goto M., Kanda N., Zerbini A.N., Kerem D., Watanabe K., Bessho Y., Hasegawa M., Nielsen R., Larsen F., Palsbøll P.J.","Radiation and speciation of pelagic organisms during periods of global warming: The case of the common minke whale, Balaenoptera acutorostrata",2007,"Molecular Ecology","16","7",,"1481","1495",,,10.1111/j.1365-294X.2007.03244.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33947507089&partnerID=40&md5=c29f7616dbfa3c4a8aab902616071335","Institute of Cetacean Research, 4-5 Toyomi-cho, Chuo-ku, Tokyo 104-0055, Japan; School of Aquatic and Fishery Sciences, University of Washington, Seattle, WA 98195-5020, United States; Recanati Institute for Maritime Studies, University of Haifa, Mount Carmel, Haifa 31905, Israel; Institute for Cellular and Molecular Biology, University of Texas at Austin, Moffett Molecular Biology Building A4800, 2500 Speedway, Austin, TX 78712-1095, United States; RIKEN GSC, 1-7-22 Suehiro-cho, Tsurumi-ku, Yokohama 230-0045, Japan; Institute of Statistical Mathematics, Tokyo 106-8569, Japan; Department of Biosystems Science, Graduate University for Advanced Studies, Hayama 240-0193, Japan; Bioinformatics Centre, University of Copenhagen, Universitetsparken, 2100 Copenhagen Ø, Denmark; Department of Biometrics, 439 Warren Hall, Cornell University, Ithaca, NY 14853-7801, United States; Danish Institute for Fisheries Research, Charlottenlund Castle, DK-2920 Charlottenlund, Denmark; Department of Genetics, Microbiology and Toxicology, Stockholm University, S-106 91 Stockholm, Sweden","Pastene, L.A., Institute of Cetacean Research, 4-5 Toyomi-cho, Chuo-ku, Tokyo 104-0055, Japan; Goto, M., Institute of Cetacean Research, 4-5 Toyomi-cho, Chuo-ku, Tokyo 104-0055, Japan; Kanda, N., Institute of Cetacean Research, 4-5 Toyomi-cho, Chuo-ku, Tokyo 104-0055, Japan; Zerbini, A.N., School of Aquatic and Fishery Sciences, University of Washington, Seattle, WA 98195-5020, United States; Kerem, D., Recanati Institute for Maritime Studies, University of Haifa, Mount Carmel, Haifa 31905, Israel; Watanabe, K., Institute for Cellular and Molecular Biology, University of Texas at Austin, Moffett Molecular Biology Building A4800, 2500 Speedway, Austin, TX 78712-1095, United States; Bessho, Y., RIKEN GSC, 1-7-22 Suehiro-cho, Tsurumi-ku, Yokohama 230-0045, Japan; Hasegawa, M., Institute of Statistical Mathematics, Tokyo 106-8569, Japan, Department of Biosystems Science, Graduate University for Advanced Studies, Hayama 240-0193, Japan; Nielsen, R., Bioinformatics Centre, University of Copenhagen, Universitetsparken, 2100 Copenhagen Ø, Denmark, Department of Biometrics, 439 Warren Hall, Cornell University, Ithaca, NY 14853-7801, United States; Larsen, F., Danish Institute for Fisheries Research, Charlottenlund Castle, DK-2920 Charlottenlund, Denmark; Palsbøll, P.J., Department of Genetics, Microbiology and Toxicology, Stockholm University, S-106 91 Stockholm, Sweden","How do populations of highly mobile species inhabiting open environments become reproductively isolated and evolve into new species? We test the hypothesis that elevated ocean-surface temperatures can facilitate allopatry among pelagic populations and thus promote speciation. Oceanographic modelling has shown that increasing surface temperatures cause localization and reduction of upwelling, leading to fragmentation of feeding areas critical to pelagic species. We test our hypothesis by genetic analyses of populations of two closely related baleen whales, the Antarctic minke whale (Balaenoptera bonaerensis) and common minke whale (Balaenoptera acutorostrata) whose current distributions and migration patterns extent are largely determined by areas of consistent upwelling with high primary production. Phylogeographic and population genetic analyses of mitochondrial DNA control-region nucleotide sequences collected from 467 whales sampled in four different ocean basins were employed to infer the evolutionary relationship among populations of B. acutorostrata by rooting an intraspecific phylogeny with a population of B. bonaerensis. Our findings suggest that the two species diverged in the Southern Hemisphere less than 5 million years ago (Ma). This estimate places the speciation event during a period of extended global warming in the Pliocene. We propose that elevated ocean temperatures in the period facilitated allopatric speciation by disrupting the continuous belt of upwelling maintained by the Antarctic Circumpolar Current. Our analyses revealed that the current populations of B. acutorostrata likely diverged after the Pliocene some 1.5 Ma when global temperatures had decreased and presumably coinciding with the re-establishment of the polar-equatorial temperature gradient that ultimately drives upwelling. In most population samples, we detected genetic signatures of exponential population expansions, consistent with the notion of increasing carrying capacity after the Pliocene. Our hypothesis that prolonged periods of global warming facilitate speciation in pelagic marine species that depend on upwelling should be tested by comparative analyses in other pelagic species. © 2007 The Authors.","Cetacea; Evolution; Expansion; Global warming; Phylogeography; Speciation","mitochondrial DNA; primer DNA; animal; article; comparative study; DNA sequence; genetics; geography; greenhouse effect; minke whale; molecular evolution; molecular genetics; nucleotide sequence; phylogeny; population dynamics; population genetics; sea; species difference; species differentiation; temperature; Animals; Base Sequence; DNA Primers; DNA, Mitochondrial; Evolution, Molecular; Genetic Speciation; Genetics, Population; Geography; Greenhouse Effect; Minke Whale; Molecular Sequence Data; Oceans and Seas; Phylogeny; Population Dynamics; Sequence Analysis, DNA; Species Specificity; Temperature; Balaenoptera; Balaenoptera acutorostrata; Balaenoptera bonaerensis; Cetacea; Mysticeti","GENBANK: EF113709, EF113710, EF113711, EF113712